<h1 style="text-align: center;display: block;margin: 0;padding: 0;color: #202020;font-family: Helvetica;font-size: 26px;font-style: normal;font-weight: bold;line-height: 125%;letter-spacing: normal;">GetSwift, Ripple and Soros</h1>

<p style="margin: 10px 0;padding: 0;mso-line-height-rule: exactly;-ms-text-size-adjust: 100%;-webkit-text-size-adjust: 100%;color: #202020;font-family: Helvetica;font-size: 16px;line-height: 150%;text-align: left;">GetSwift was the talk of town <em>before</em> they were pinged by the AFR for hiding information from the market.<br>
     <br>
    The firm offers a delivery app, and in 2017 motored to a $700 million value, on the back of a steady stream of contract announcements, with firms ranging from the local Red Rooster to Amazon.<br>
     <br>
    But many sensed something was up.  <br>
     <br>
    At first, GetSwift was given respect as a short idea.<br>
     <br>
    People did the calculations, and suggested the basic economics of their business didn’t fly, namely, that the amount of deliveries at 29c each they’d have to handle to justify their valuation.<br>
     <br>
    To pull A$100m in revenue and justify a A$700m valuation, that’s over 300 million deliveries, or close (enough) to a million a day. That’s a lot of restaurant deliveries.<br>
     <br>
    Soon enough, as GetSwift’s announcements became more and more optimistic and vague, the calculations disappeared in the face of common sense.<br>
     <br>
    Why on earth would Amazon outsource their last mile delivery technology?<br>
     <br>
    And if they did, why would they outsource to an unknown Aussie start-up with $300k revenue?<br>
     <br>
    Surely <em>any</em> client that started paying big enough bills would bring the capability in-house. <br>
     <br>
    Only a few short weeks ago in December, the company raised $100 million – I would guess from retail punters - at a time where, in some circles at least, the firm had already become a joke.<br>
     <br>
    (Though true blame can only lie with the people running the show. Their investors trusted them.)<br>
     <br>
    The firm’s list of client validators could be a case study in Robert Caldiani’s <em>Influence</em>. <br>
     <br>
    If a firm signs a serious enough deal it will be announced by <strong><em>both</em> </strong>sides. Amazon refused to confirm their relationship with GetSwift.<br>
     <br>
    There are plenty of retail punters out there who ‘invest’ off announcements. Many will now learn for the first time that announcements of new clients and contracts are only as good as the detail provided.<br>
     <br>
    GetSwift charmed this segment of the market to perfection.<br>
    <br>
