     <a href="http://www.afr.com/business/banking-and-finance/hedge-funds/getswift-too-fast-for-its-own-good-20180116-h0ji3t" style="mso-line-height-rule: exactly;-ms-text-size-adjust: 100%;-webkit-text-size-adjust: 100%;color: #2BAADF;font-weight: normal;text-decoration: underline;">Original article</a> – very decent reporting from the AFR.<br>
    <br>
    Why was it so convincing?<br>
                              <br>
    Perhaps it was the CEO’s AFL background. Or perhaps it was that seductive allure of technology, the returns from which are so desired yet so elusive in the Australian market.<br>
     <br>
    Chasing small-cap momentum has been a winning strategy for so long that many in the market won’t remember a time where <em>CBA</em> needed the Government’s help to raise capital.<br>
     <br>
    Soros wrote, in his rarely imitated Hungarian-philosopher style, about the two-way relationship between prices and fundamentals.<br>
     <br>
    Financial analysts seem to study companies in greater and greater detail, trying to predict future prices , on often only the current fair value.<br>
     <br>
    Soros argued – and we agree – that market prices themselves affect the fundamentals.<br>
     <br>
    Companies seen to be kicking goals can raise the capital to actually achieve those goals, and leave plenty of equity for the founders to boot.<br>
     <br>
    In many cases, the prices shown in the market drive how the fundamentals change through time.<br>
     <br>
    Those reflexive dynamics are equally powerful in reverse.<br>
     <br>
    By spruiking their stock, GetSwift raised so much money they were in a strong position as any to build a lasting app.  <br>
     <br>
    But if this article was published four weeks ago, the firm’s capital raising wouldn’t have moved past the drawing board.  <br>
     <br>
    GetSwift IPO’d at 20c barely a year ago, and traded as high as $4.3. It traded at $2.97 on Friday, and is now in a trading halt.<br>
     <br>
    There seem to be many situations like this in the market right now. I can’t remember an atmosphere more congenial to this kind of play. GetSwift isn’t the only company at >100x revenue.<br>
     <br>
    Tesla is a great example of how selling a vision - and more importantly in this case, preselling a bunch of cars - opened financial markets, allowing them to raise debt and equity at such high prices that their vision becomes in reach. Personally I think raising debt was a huge mistake, but that’s an article for another day.<br>
     <br>
    Ripple, the cryptocurrency, is a more outrageous example, on a far grander scale than GetSwift.<br>
     <br>
    Soros’s reflexivity is a fine model for thinking about equity markets and how they interact with the rest of the world, through IPOs, capital raises, buyouts and so on. But it also sheds insight on currencies, and speculative mania of all kinds.<br>
     <br>
    Like GetSwift, Ripple's founders have mastered the art and timing of empty announcements, enthralling today's feisty crop of speculators.<br>
    <br>
    The details released tend to show that Ripple’s technology, rather than the use of their coin, is being considered. And there’s a vast chasm between how Ripple describes their technology, and how their clients refer to it.<br>
     <br>
    Like GetSwift, Ripple’s founders are audacious, reserving the vast majority of the coin supply to themselves, and are now some of the richest men in the world.<br>
     <br>
    The founder’s holdings were recently pegged at $76 billion.<br>
     <br>
    There are few markets where this kind of brazenness is rewarded. We are currently in one.<br>
     <br>
    As these schemes start to unwind, there’s a growing chance that they will tip the rest of the market.<br>
     <br>
    We are watching carefully.<br>
     <br>
    Michael<br>
